<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="2" pageNumber="48" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1926,2030]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1438,152,1376]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="2" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,343,1926,1952]" pageId="2" pageNumber="48">Description</emphasis>
. As stated by P. Knight-Jones (
<number box="[719,780,1927,1953]" pageId="2" pageNumber="48" value="1978.0">1978</number>
) the present species is, compared to other spirorbids, a very large species, attaining a coil diameter of 5.0mm when coiled in the same plane. In addition to the generic diagnosis above, see P. Knight-Jones (
<number box="[692,756,2004,2030]" pageId="2" pageNumber="48" value="1978.0">1978</number>
: 
<number box="[767,871,2004,2030]" pageId="2" pageNumber="48" value="233.5" valueMax="234.0" valueMin="233.0">233–234</number>
) and P. &amp; 
<bibRefCitation author="Knight-Jones" box="[993,1307,2004,2030]" pageId="2" pageNumber="50" refString="Knight-Jones, P. &amp; E. W. Knight-Jones (1994) Spirorbidae (Polychaeta) from Signy Island, South Orkneys, including three new species. Ophelia, 40 (2), 75 - 94." type="journal article" year="1994">
E. W. Knight-Jones (
<number box="[1237,1298,2004,2030]" pageId="2" pageNumber="48" value="1994.0">1994</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
for further details relating to the tube, worm, chaetae, egg-sac attachment, and other characters. The egg sac and its attachment to the specialized process in the dorsal thoracic groove are shown in 
<figureCitation box="[1090,1180,190,216]" captionStart="FIGURE 2. A – E" captionStartId="2.[151,255,1749,1773]" captionTargetBox="[185,1435,411,1748]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[132,1456,377,1775]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. A – E, Knightjonesia platyspira (P. Knight-Jones, 1978): same scale for all; w— wing. A, Enlarged view of operculum of specimen figured in Fig. 1. B – D, stages in opercular wing development observed in paratypes; B also shows the sub-quadrangular talon. E: whole worm showing the winged opercular peduncle and the egg sac with its specialized attachment stalk to the dorsal thoracic groove." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186795/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="49">
Fig. 
<number box="[1143,1159,190,216]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="2.0">2</number>
E
</figureCitation>
. The brief description which follows is limited to the character of its winged opercular peduncle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1438,152,1376]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49">
Initially the wings are short and faintly recognizable (
<figureCitation box="[828,927,268,294]" captionStart="FIGURE 2. A – E" captionStartId="2.[151,255,1749,1773]" captionTargetBox="[185,1435,411,1748]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[132,1456,377,1775]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. A – E, Knightjonesia platyspira (P. Knight-Jones, 1978): same scale for all; w— wing. A, Enlarged view of operculum of specimen figured in Fig. 1. B – D, stages in opercular wing development observed in paratypes; B also shows the sub-quadrangular talon. E: whole worm showing the winged opercular peduncle and the egg sac with its specialized attachment stalk to the dorsal thoracic groove." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186795/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="49">
Fig. 
<number box="[883,898,268,294]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="2.0">2</number>
B
</figureCitation>
). In a later stage (
<figureCitation box="[1138,1230,268,294]" captionStart="FIGURE 2. A – E" captionStartId="2.[151,255,1749,1773]" captionTargetBox="[185,1435,411,1748]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[132,1456,377,1775]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. A – E, Knightjonesia platyspira (P. Knight-Jones, 1978): same scale for all; w— wing. A, Enlarged view of operculum of specimen figured in Fig. 1. B – D, stages in opercular wing development observed in paratypes; B also shows the sub-quadrangular talon. E: whole worm showing the winged opercular peduncle and the egg sac with its specialized attachment stalk to the dorsal thoracic groove." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186795/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="49">
Fig. 
<number box="[1193,1209,268,294]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="2.0">2</number>
C
</figureCitation>
), they are narrow and elongated. The more fully developed wings are shown in 
<figureCitation box="[873,956,306,332]" captionStart="FIGURE 2. A – E" captionStartId="2.[151,255,1749,1773]" captionTargetBox="[185,1435,411,1748]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[132,1456,377,1775]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. A – E, Knightjonesia platyspira (P. Knight-Jones, 1978): same scale for all; w— wing. A, Enlarged view of operculum of specimen figured in Fig. 1. B – D, stages in opercular wing development observed in paratypes; B also shows the sub-quadrangular talon. E: whole worm showing the winged opercular peduncle and the egg sac with its specialized attachment stalk to the dorsal thoracic groove." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186795/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="49">
Figs. 
<number box="[939,956,306,332]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
, A, D &amp; E.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="49" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1438,152,1376]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,339,344,370]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49">Etymology.</emphasis>
The genus is dedicated to both Prof. E. Wyn Knight-Jones &amp; the late Dr. Phyllis Knight- Jones, in appreciation of their numerous contributions to our knowledge of the biology and systematics of serpulimorph and sabellid polychaetes, especially spirorbids, besides other areas.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1438,152,1376]" box="[198,1225,461,487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49">
Taxonomy of genera belonging to the subfamily Romanchellinae P. Knight-Jones, 
<number box="[1166,1225,461,487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="1978.0">1978</number>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1438,152,1376]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49">
Among the characters of the subfamily Romanchellinae, included by P. Knight-Jones (
<number box="[1226,1290,500,526]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="1978.0">1978</number>
: 
<number box="[1303,1349,500,526]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="229.0">229</number>
) and P. &amp; 
<bibRefCitation author="Knight-Jones" box="[183,570,538,564]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" refString="Knight-Jones, P. &amp; E. W. Knight-Jones (1994) Spirorbidae (Polychaeta) from Signy Island, South Orkneys, including three new species. Ophelia, 40 (2), 75 - 94." type="journal article" year="1994">
E. W. Knight-Jones (
<number box="[445,513,538,564]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="1994.0">1994</number>
: 
<number box="[526,561,538,564]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="79.0">79</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, is that the embryos are raised within the tube in an egg sac attached anteriorly by a specialized process to the dorsal thoracic faecal groove. P. &amp; 
<bibRefCitation author="Knight-Jones" box="[1069,1436,577,603]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" refString="Knight-Jones, P. &amp; E. W. Knight-Jones (1994) Spirorbidae (Polychaeta) from Signy Island, South Orkneys, including three new species. Ophelia, 40 (2), 75 - 94." type="journal article" year="1994">
E. W. Knight-Jones (
<number box="[1319,1384,577,603]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="1994.0">1994</number>
: 
<number box="[1396,1427,577,603]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="79.0">79</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
also state that the members of the subfamily are the only spirorbids that possess brush-like abdominal chaetae. P. Knight-Jones (
<number box="[361,425,654,680]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="1978.0">1978</number>
: 
<number box="[437,542,654,680]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="231.5" valueMax="234.0" valueMin="229.0">229–234</number>
) included the following genera under the subfamily: 
<taxonomicName authority="Caullery &amp; Mesnil (1897)" authorityName="Caullery &amp; Mesnil" authorityYear="1897" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Romanchella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1172,1327,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="49">Romanchella</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Caullery" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" refString="Caullery, M., &amp; Mesnil, F. (1897) Etudes sur la morphologie comparee et la phylogenenie des Especes des Spirorbes. Bulletin Scientifique de la France et de la Belgique, 30 (4) 9, 185 - 233." type="journal article" year="1897">
Caullery &amp; Mesnil (
<number box="[280,343,693,719]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" value="1897.0">1897</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<typeStatus box="[365,415,693,719]" pageId="3" pageNumber="49">type</typeStatus>
species 
<emphasis box="[516,613,693,718]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="49">Spirorbi</emphasis>
s 
<taxonomicName authority="Caullery &amp; Mesnil (1897)" authorityName="Caullery &amp; Mesnil" authorityYear="1897" box="[632,1221,693,719]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Romanchella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="3" pageNumber="49" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="perrieri" subGenus="Romanchella">
